'''George Dempsey'''  (1854 – 29 June 1924) born in the parish of St. Mary's, Dublin was a teacher of English at [[Belvedere College]], [[Dublin]], Ireland, who taught English to the writer [[James Joyce]] and later the poet [[Austin Clarke (poet)|Austin Clarke]] during the time they attended the Jesuit school.<ref name="companion">''Critical companion to James Joyce: a literary reference to his life and work'', by A. Nicholas Fargnoli and Michael Patrick Gillespie. {{ISBN|978-0-8160-6689-6}}</ref>  At the same time he ran a grocer's shop and post office at 13 Dunville Ave, Rathmines.<ref>HumphrysFamilyTree.com, [http://humphrysfamilytree.com/Flanagan/dempsey.html] </ref> The character of Mr. Tate in Joyce's novels ''[[A Portrait of the Artist as a Young Man]]'' and ''[[Stephen Hero]]'' is based on George Dempsey.<ref name="companion" /><ref>See also the contribution entitled "Heresy in his Essay" in ''Portraits: Belvedere College Dublin 1832-1982'', pub. Gill & MacMillan, 1982, Ed. John Bowman & Ronan O'Donoghue</ref> George Dempsey died at 13 Dunville Avenue at the age of 70.

An annual prize in memory of Dempsey is awarded each year at Belvedere College to a student who has excelled in English writing.

